II. Data Cleaning¶

A.“Leakage” is a term used in machine learning for when a model makes decisions using information that it would not actually have, resulting in unnaturally high performance. This is similar to what occurs when two variables have perfect collinearity. What would leakage look like in the context of this problem and dataset?¶

In this problem set, the dataset we are using contains data that can be used to predict whether or not an arraignment can occur and also contains data that discusses the aftermath of the arraignment decision. As such, because the data contains information that would only be there after the arraignment decision was made, the leakage can occur by using those columns to predict whether or not the defendent should be remanded or not (kept in jail or let out before hearing). Furthermore, leakage would also looks like letting in columns or data with repetitive information in columns/rows.

I will drop Offense Month and Offense year because they do not help answer the question asked in the problem set, and contain many null values. I will also drop the columns of Top_Charge_at_Arrest and Top_Charge_at_Arraign because they are redundant; the information found those rows are in other rows. Furthermore, the Age_at_Arrest column is recorded when the the police officer guesses the age of the offender at the time of their arrest. There are a lot of values that are 0s in those that are in place of a null value, so I will be deleting this column since it is faulty (containing a lot of null values) and hard to guess, so its validity is questionable. Finally, the columns of 'Judge_Name', 'Court_Name', 'Top_Arrest_Article_Section','Top_Arraign_Article_Section' each have at least 500 unique values, so keeping them would be very computationally heavy, since we'd need to fix our dataset so that it can pass through the partitioning that sci-kit learn does. They also aren't useful to answer the question being asked in this problem set, so I will drop them. The columns of 'Arraign Charge Category','Representation_Type', 'App_Count_Arraign_to_Dispo_Released', 'App_Count_Arraign_to_Dispo_Detained','App_Count_Arraign_to_Dispo_Total' were redundant and difficult to work with due to the amount of unique values, and did not help answer the question being posed by the problem set.

C. What should the timeframe of the dataset be if we’re interested in model predictions under the revised statute that reinstituted opportunities for cash bail? How do you address this in your data cleaning?¶

The reforms went into place on July 1, 2020, broadening the situations under which cash bail could be set. I would reflect this in my data cleaning by removing the rows from the columns "Arrest Year" and "Arrest_Month" that contain dates prior to July 1st 2020.

B. Choose three different prediction techniques that are appropriate to the problem at hand. Describe the basic mechanism of each, benefits and drawbacks, and any other criteria you factored into your decision. Why is each a reasonable choice for this context?¶

Random Forest Classifier¶

  • Basic Mechanism: Random Forest Classifier is an ensemble learning technique that combines multiple decision trees to make predictions. Each tree in the forest is trained on a random subset of features and a random subset of data points, which introduces randomness and diversity into the model. The final prediction is obtained by averaging or taking a majority vote of the predictions from individual trees.
  • Benefits: Random Forest Classifier can handle a wide range of data types, including categorical and numerical features, and can capture complex nonlinear relationships and interactions among features. It is less prone to overfitting compared to single decision trees, as the averaging or majority voting of predictions from multiple trees helps to reduce variance and improve model generalization ability. In this case, this model is ideal for the binary classifiers that we use to predict whether or not someone is Remanded at Arraign.
  • Drawbacks: Random Forest Classifier may require careful tuning of hyperparameters such as the number of trees, maximum depth of each tree, and the number of features to consider at each split. The model may also become less interpretable compared to single decision trees, as the predictions are obtained from an ensemble of trees.
  • Other Criteria: Random Forest Classifier is a good choice when you want to build a robust and accurate model that can handle complex patterns in the data. It is suitable for both classification and regression tasks and can be considered when interpretability is not a primary concern. It is well-suited for binary prediction classification tasks due to its ability to handle complex interactions among features and capture non-linear relationships in the data. The randomness introduced during tree construction helps to reduce overfitting, making it more robust and reliable for binary prediction tasks. Additionally, Random Forest Classifier can handle high-dimensional datasets with a large number of features, making it suitable for binary classification tasks that involve a large number of predictors.

Ridge Classifier¶

  • Basic Mechanism: Ridge Classifier is a linear classifier that uses L2 regularization to shrink the magnitude of the coefficients in the model. It minimizes the sum of squared errors between the predicted and actual values, subject to a constraint that limits the size of the coefficients. This constraint reduces the variance of the model and prevents overfitting by penalizing large coefficients.
  • Benefits: Ridge Classifier can handle high-dimensional datasets with a large number of features, as it is able to select a subset of informative features and shrink the coefficients of less important features towards zero. It is less prone to overfitting compared to ordinary least squares regression, which can be useful when dealing with noisy or sparse data. Ridge Classifier is also computationally efficient and can be used with both binary and multi-class classification problems.
  • Drawbacks: Ridge Classifier assumes that the relationship between the predictors and the target variable is linear and may not perform well when there are non-linear relationships or interactions among features. It also requires tuning of the regularization parameter to balance bias and variance in the model, which can be a challenge. Additionally, Ridge Classifier may not perform well when there are irrelevant features in the data, as the regularization penalty may not be able to eliminate them completely.
  • Other Criteria: Ridge Classifier is a reasonable choice for the context of predicting Remanded_to_Jail_at_Arraign, a binary categorical variable of Yes or No. This is because the dataset may have many features, and Ridge Classifier is able to handle high-dimensional data efficiently. Additionally, the regularization term in Ridge Classifier can help to prevent overfitting and improve the generalization ability of the model. Since the relationship between the predictor variables and the response variable may not be known in advance, a linear classifier such as Ridge Classifier may be a good starting point to explore the data and identify the most important features. Ridge Classifier is also computationally efficient and can handle both binary and multi-class classification problems, making it a versatile choice for classification tasks.

Extra Trees Classifier¶

  • Basic Mechanism: Extra Trees Classifier is an ensemble learning technique that combines multiple decision trees to make predictions. However, unlike traditional decision trees, Extra Trees Classifier introduces additional randomness by selecting random subsets of features and splitting points during the tree construction process. This results in a more diverse set of trees and can improve the model's generalization ability.
  • Benefits: Extra Trees Classifier can handle a large number of features and is less prone to overfitting compared to traditional decision trees, as the randomness introduced during tree construction reduces the risk of trees memorizing the training data. It can also capture complex nonlinear relationships and interactions among features, making it suitable for datasets with complex patterns.
  • Drawbacks: Extra Trees Classifier may require careful tuning of hyperparameters such as the number of trees and the maximum depth of each tree to achieve optimal performance. The randomness introduced during tree construction may also make the model less interpretable compared to single decision trees.
  • Other Criteria: Extra Trees Classifier is a good choice when you have a large dataset with complex patterns and you want to reduce the risk of overfitting. It can also be considered when interpretability is not a priority, and you are looking for an ensemble method that can capture complex nonlinear relationships. This makes it ideal for binary prediction classification tasks where complex patterns and interactions among features need to be captured. The randomness introduced during tree construction helps to reduce overfitting, making it more reliable for binary classification tasks. Additionally, Extra Trees Classifier can handle large datasets with high-dimensional features, making it suitable for binary classification tasks that involve a large number of predictors.

It appears that the tuned model has a higher recall score, while the untuned model has a higher precision score. This means that the tuned model is better at identifying the positive class (people who are remanded to jail), but at the cost of more false positives. On the other hand, the untuned model is better at avoiding false positives, but at the cost of missing more true positives. If the goal of our model is to identify as many people who should be remanded to jail as possible, even if it means some false positives, then the tuned model with higher recall is likely the better choice. However, if the goal is to minimize false positives and ensure that only those who truly need to be remanded to jail are, then the untuned model with higher precision may be the better choice. It is important to note that both models have a high accuracy score, so both are performing well overall.

  • Mean Judge Decision: This value represents the proportion of individuals in the group who were remanded at arraign, based on the judge's decision.

  • Mean Model Probability Score: This value represents the average probability score assigned by the model to the group. The probability score indicates how likely the model thinks an individual in the group is to be remanded at arraign.

  • Mean Model Prediction: This value represents the proportion of individuals in the group that the model predicted would be remanded at arraign.

For example, looking at the first row of the table, for the entire dataset, the mean judge decision is 0.033071. This means that about 3.3% of individuals in the dataset were remanded at arraign, based on the judge's decision. The mean model probability score is 0.033737, indicating that the model thinks the individuals in the dataset have about a 3.3% chance of being remanded at arraign. The mean model prediction is 0.020859, meaning that the model predicted that about 2.1% of individuals in the dataset would be remanded at arraign.

The mean model prediction for the Black group is also higher at 0.026779, meaning that the model predicted a higher proportion of Black individuals would be remanded at arraign.

In general, comparing the mean judge decision to the mean model prediction and probability score can help us evaluate the accuracy of the model in predicting the judge's decision. If the mean model prediction and probability score are similar to the mean judge decision, then the model is performing well in predicting the judge's decision. If there is a large difference between the mean model prediction and the mean judge decision, then the model may not be accurate in predicting the judge's decision.
